The male of 

C. hanangensis

is characterized by having the apical margin of clypeus black and tridentate (

), the mandibles are edentate internally, the flagellomeres VIII-XI have small tyloidea (

), the prosternum has no transverse carina, the propodeal enclosure is shallowly irregularly obliquely ridged and the lateral- and medo-longitudinal furrows are indistinctly developed. Additionally, the petiolus is slightly longer than wide, the tegulae and the wings are ferruginous and the genitalia are characteristically shaped (

